1
00:00:00,340 --> 00:00:04,059
In this video we are going to learn domain driven design.

2
00:00:04,090 --> 00:00:06,250
So what is domain driven design?

3
00:00:06,280 --> 00:00:13,300
Domain driven design has been around since Eric Evans published his book about the subject in 2003.

4
00:00:13,690 --> 00:00:18,370
Domain driven design is not an improved technology or specific method.

5
00:00:18,430 --> 00:00:20,020
Domain driven design is.

6
00:00:20,020 --> 00:00:26,890
Solving a complex problem is to break the problem into smaller parts and focus on the smaller problems

7
00:00:26,890 --> 00:00:28,990
that are relatively easy.

8
00:00:29,590 --> 00:00:36,280
A complex domain may contain subdomains, and some of the sub domains can combine and grouping with

9
00:00:36,280 --> 00:00:39,550
each other for common rules and responsibilities.

10
00:00:40,390 --> 00:00:42,940
So domain driven design has two types.

11
00:00:42,940 --> 00:00:47,230
These are the strategic and tactical domain driven design.

12
00:00:47,620 --> 00:00:52,720
Strategic domain driven design is about understanding and modeling the business domain.

13
00:00:52,720 --> 00:00:58,330
It involves identifying the different domains, their sub domains, and how they interact with each

14
00:00:58,330 --> 00:00:58,900
other.

15
00:00:59,620 --> 00:01:05,740
In tactical domain driven design is more about the implementation details and provide design patterns

16
00:01:05,740 --> 00:01:10,990
including the patterns like entities, value objects, aggregates, and so on.

17
00:01:11,110 --> 00:01:16,480
For this video, we will focus on the strategic domain driven design and its key concepts.

18
00:01:17,590 --> 00:01:23,710
In order to understand domain driven design, some basic concepts need to be mastered and these are

19
00:01:23,710 --> 00:01:29,710
the domain subdomain, ubiquitous language, bounded context and context mapping.

20
00:01:29,710 --> 00:01:31,630
So let me start with the domain.

21
00:01:31,930 --> 00:01:37,240
The domain is the sphere of the knowledge and activity around which the application logic revolves.

22
00:01:37,240 --> 00:01:44,230
It represents the problem space and the array of the expertise or business need that the software addresses.

23
00:01:44,260 --> 00:01:50,350
An example of the domain in e-commerce application domain might include ordering, inventory management

24
00:01:50,350 --> 00:01:52,300
and customer support, and so on.

25
00:01:52,990 --> 00:01:55,330
The second concept is sub domain.

26
00:01:55,420 --> 00:02:01,270
A sub domain is a part of the domain and represents a specific area of the expertise within the overall

27
00:02:01,270 --> 00:02:01,930
domain.

28
00:02:01,960 --> 00:02:08,979
Each sub domain has its unique logic and rules, and another concept is ubiquitous language, which

29
00:02:08,979 --> 00:02:15,820
is a common language used by the developers and the domain experts in order to ensure clarity and consistency.

30
00:02:15,850 --> 00:02:20,830
It is crucial for this language to be used in both discussions and in the code base.

31
00:02:20,830 --> 00:02:27,010
It helps to avoid misunderstanding and ensures that all stakeholders have a common understanding of

32
00:02:27,010 --> 00:02:28,180
the domain concepts.

33
00:02:28,780 --> 00:02:31,990
And another important concept is bounded context.

34
00:02:31,990 --> 00:02:38,200
Bounded context is the grouping of the closely related scopes that we can say logical boundaries.

35
00:02:38,200 --> 00:02:44,860
Bounded context is a logical boundary that represents the smaller problem particles of the complex domain

36
00:02:44,860 --> 00:02:48,430
that are self-consistent and as dependent as possible.

37
00:02:48,430 --> 00:02:54,910
It is a central pattern in domain driven design, and help to manage complexity by dividing these domain

38
00:02:54,910 --> 00:02:56,290
into manageable parts.

39
00:02:56,320 --> 00:02:59,710
Each bounded context can have its database schema.

40
00:02:59,710 --> 00:03:02,860
It is called modules and it is team working on it.

41
00:03:03,370 --> 00:03:07,360
And another domain driven concept is context mapping pattern.

42
00:03:07,360 --> 00:03:13,300
In DDT, we can use context mapping pattern for identification of bounded contexts.

43
00:03:13,300 --> 00:03:19,270
With context mapping pattern, we can identify the whole bounded context in the application and with

44
00:03:19,270 --> 00:03:20,530
their logical boundaries.

45
00:03:20,530 --> 00:03:25,150
And the context map is a way to define logical boundaries between the domains.

